(1, 'Increase monitoring and maintain proper field drainage.', '', 0, 25, 2, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '', '', 1, '', 1, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.520867', '', '', '', 70),
(2, 'Apply fungicide spray (e.g., propiconazole) within 48 hours.', '', 25, 60, 2, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '', '', 1, '', 1, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.520867', '', '', '', 70),
(3, 'Consider immediate integrated pest management and consult DA officer.', '', 60, 101, 2, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '', '', 1, '', 1, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.520867', '', '', '', 70),
(4, 'No immediate action required. Continue field monitoring and good agronomic practices.', 'Maintain current good practices and monitor regularly to keep plants healthy.', 0, 100, 1, '• No chemical application needed\n• Avoid unnecessary pesticide use (protects beneficial insects)', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '• Continue current good agronomic practices\n• Monitor fields 2-3 times per week\n• Maintain balanced fertilization\n• Proper water management (2-5 cm depth during vegetative stage)\n• Continue weed control\n• Scout for early signs of pest or disease', '• Resistant variety\n• Balanced nutrition\n• Good water management\n• Proper spacing\n• Field sanitation\n• Favorable weather', 1, '• Regular field scouting\n• Maintain field sanitation\n• Proper nutrient management\n• Continue good water management\n• Keep records of field activities\n• Be prepared to respond quickly if problems emerge', 1, '• Green, vigorous leaves\n• No visible lesions, spots, or discoloration\n• Normal growth and development\n• Good tiller formation', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.123400', '', '', '', 70),
(6, 'Use resistant varieties, balance fertilization (especially P and K), remove infected debris, apply fungicide if spreading.', 'Brown spot management focuses on balanced nutrition and field sanitation.', 0, 100, 2, '• Fungicide seed treatment (e.g., mancozeb, carbendazim) before planting\n• Foliar fungicide (e.g., azoxystrobin, propiconazole) if disease is spreading\n• Apply fungicide at tillering and booting stages if needed\n• Follow product label for dosage and application timing', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '• Plant resistant or tolerant varieties\n• Apply balanced fertilization - avoid excess nitrogen\n• Supplement with P and K based on soil test results\n• Maintain adequate soil moisture\n• Remove and bury infected plant debris after harvest\n• Practice crop rotation with legumes to improve soil health', '• High nitrogen fertilization\n• Phosphorus (P) and Potassium (K) deficiency\n• Physical injuries to plants\n• Poor soil fertility\n• Moisture stress', 1, '• Soil testing to identify nutrient deficiencies\n• Use healthy certified seeds\n• Avoid mechanical damage during field operations\n• Ensure proper field leveling for uniform water distribution\n• Monitor fields regularly during vegetative growth', 1, '• Small circular to oval brown spots on leaves\n• Spots may have gray or white centers\n• Lesions may coalesce on severely infected leaves\n• Can appear on leaf sheath, panicle, and grains', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.942957', '', '', '', 70),
(7, 'Apply recommended systemic fungicide at booting stage and avoid late nitrogen.', '', 0, 100, 7, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '', '', 1, '', 1, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.520867', '', '', '', 70),
(8, 'Plant resistant varieties. Avoid excessive nitrogen. Balance K and Mg. Maintain field sanitation and proper spacing.', 'Leaf scald management emphasizes balanced nutrition and cultural practices.', 0, 100, 8, '• Generally, chemical control is not primary management strategy\n• Copper-based bactericides may provide some suppression\n• Focus on nutritional and cultural management first', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '• Use resistant or tolerant varieties\n• Avoid excessive nitrogen - follow soil test recommendations\n• Apply adequate Potassium and Magnesium based on soil analysis\n• Improve field drainage\n• Maintain proper plant spacing\n• Remove infected plant debris\n• Avoid field operations when plants are wet', '• High nitrogen application\n• Low Potassium (K) and Magnesium (Mg) levels\n• Root injuries\n• High humidity conditions\n• Poor field drainage', 1, '• Regular soil testing to monitor K and Mg levels\n• Balanced fertilizer programs\n• Proper water management\n• Field sanitation between crops\n• Monitor plant health throughout season', 1, '• Lesions on leaf blades, often at tips\n• Yellowing or pale green coloration of leaves\n• May cause reduced tillering\n• Lesions may have alternating light and dark zones', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.997665', '', '', '', 70),
(9, 'Use resistant varieties. Apply balanced fertilization (especially potash). Remove infected debris. Apply fungicide if spreading rapidly.', 'Narrow brown spot is managed through variety selection, balanced nutrition, and sanitation.', 0, 100, 9, '• Fungicide application if disease is spreading rapidly\n• Benzimidazole fungicides (e.g., carbendazim) may be effective\n• Strobilurin fungicides as alternative\n• Apply at early infection stage for best results\n• Follow label instructions for timing and dosage', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '• Plant resistant or tolerant varieties\n• Apply balanced fertilization with adequate potassium\n• Maintain proper plant spacing for air circulation\n• Remove and destroy infected plant debris\n• Practice crop rotation\n• Ensure proper field leveling for uniform growth', '• Susceptible rice variety\n• High humidity\n• Nutrient imbalance (especially K deficiency)\n• Dense planting\n• Poor air circulation', 1, '• Soil testing to identify potassium deficiency\n• Use certified healthy seeds\n• Field sanitation after harvest\n• Monitor fields during susceptible growth stages\n• Coordinate with DA for resistant variety recommendations', 1, '• Narrow brown lesions parallel to leaf veins\n• Lesions elongated along leaf blade\n• May cause stunted growth in severe cases\n• Often appears during tillering to booting stage', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.013493', '', '', '', 70),
(10, 'Spray fungicide at heading and ensure uniform water depth across the field.', '', 0, 100, 10, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '', '', 1, '', 1, '', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.520867', '', '', '', 70),
(11, 'Manual collection of adults. Encourage natural predators. Apply insecticide only when population exceeds threshold (2-3 adults per hill).', 'Rice hispa management emphasizes biological control and threshold-based insecticide use.', 0, 100, 11, '• Use insecticide ONLY when threshold exceeded (2-3 adults per hill)\n• Spot treatment of hotspots rather than whole field\n• Fipronil or chlorantraniliprole (follow label)\n• Apply during early morning when adults are sluggish\n• Avoid broad-spectrum insecticides that kill natural enemies', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '• Manual collection of adult beetles in early morning (collect in water)\n• Clip and remove infested leaf tips with larvae inside\n• Avoid very dense planting\n• Remove weeds that can host hispa\n• Allow field to dry between crops (breaks pest cycle)\n• Encourage natural enemies: wasps, spiders, dragonflies', '• High pest population carryover\n• Dense planting with overlapping leaves\n• Continuous rice cropping without fallow\n• Destruction of natural enemies by insecticides', 1, '• Scout fields 2-3 times per week during vegetative stage\n• Maintain ecological balance - conserve natural enemies\n• Practice crop rotation with non-rice crops\n• Synchronous planting with neighbors to break pest cycle\n• Use light traps to monitor and reduce adult population\n• Avoid insecticide calendar spraying', 1, '• Linear scratches or feeding marks on leaf surface (between veins)\n• Scraping of green tissue leaving white lines\n• Stunted plants if infestation is severe\n• Adult beetles visible on leaves (metallic blue-green, 5mm long)\n• Larvae mine inside leaf tissue', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.059535', '', '', '', 70),
(12, 'Reduce planting density, improve airflow, and treat with validamycin or propiconazole.', 'ok na yan', 0, 100, 6, 'b', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', 'a', '• kulisap\r\n• lack of nutrients\r\n• madamo\r\n• tuyo\r\n• atangya', 1, 'c', 3, 'sheath blight nga yan\r\nok', '2026-03-26 10:06:52.674047', 'spray ng pang  kulisap\r\nfertilizer\r\nmag spray ng pandamo\r\npatubig\r\nspray', 'mawawala ang kulisap\r\nmanganganak at tataba ang rice\r\nmawawala ang damo\r\nmagiging malusog ang rice\r\nmawawala ang atangya', 'mataas ang severity ng palay  - kailangan mo ng magic ...joke lang', 70),
(13, 'MANDATORY: Use resistant varieties. Synchronous planting. Control green leafhoppers early. Remove infected plants immediately.', 'Tungro has no cure - management is 100% prevention through resistant varieties and vector control.', 0, 100, 5, '• NO chemical control for the virus itself\n• Insecticide to control leafhopper VECTORS during first 30 days after transplanting\n• Early vector control is critical (most infections occur in first month)\n• Systemic insecticides (imidacloprid, fipronil) at transplanting\n• Foliar insecticide (buprofezin, pymetrozine) if leafhopper numbers high\n• Monitor leafhopper population with sweep net or visual scouting', '2026-02-17 03:48:31.158866', '• CRITICAL: Plant tungro-resistant varieties (check DA list annually)\n• Synchronous planting within 2-week period in whole barangay\n• Mandatory 1-month fallow in tungro-affected areas\n• IMMEDIATE roguing: pull out and destroy infected plants as soon as detected\n• Do not leave infected plants in field (virus reservoir)\n• Plow under or burn rogued plants\n• Control volunteer rice plants and ratoons (harbor virus)\n• Remove weeds that host leafhoppers', '• Susceptible rice variety\n• Presence of infected fields in previous season or nearby\n• High green leafhopper population\n• Asynchronous planting (staggered planting dates in area)\n• No fallow period between crops\n• Continuous rice cultivation year-round', 1, '• Community-wide approach REQUIRED for tungro management\n• Barangay synchronous planting program (coordinate with DA)\n• Area-wide use of resistant varieties\n• Mandatory fallow period enforcement\n• Early detection and removal of infected plants\n• Report tungro outbreaks to Municipal Agriculture Office immediately\n• Destroy all infected plants - never use tungro field for seed production\n• Ratoon management: plow under ratoons, do not allow regrowth\n• If >5% infection: consider field abandonment and replanting with resistant variety\n• Education: Tungro cannot be cured - prevention is only option', 1, '• Mottled appearance on young leaves (yellow-green streaks)\n• Older leaves turn yellow to orange-yellow\n• Stunted growth and reduced tillering\n• Clumping/clustering of infected plants around initial infection\n• Plants may not produce panicles or produce few small panicles', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.102631', '', '', '', 70),
(14, 'Monitor field closely. Improve drainage and maintain 2-3 cm water level. Avoid nitrogen excess.', 'Early-stage BLB requires careful monitoring and preventive measures to avoid spread.', 0, 30, 4, '• Copper-based bactericides may be applied if infection spreads\r\n• Follow product label instructions carefully\r\n• Apply during early morning or late afternoon', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.894306', '• Plant resistant varieties (consult local DA for recommendations)\r\n• Use certified healthy seeds or treat seeds before planting\r\n• Maintain proper field drainage with 2-3 cm water level\r\n• Apply balanced fertilization using Leaf Color Chart\r\n• Use Minus-One Element Technique to identify nutrient needs\r\n• Adopt wider plant spacing for better air circulation\r\n• Deep plow fields and expose soil to sunlight between cropping seasons', '• Susceptible rice variety\r\n• High humidity and frequent rains\r\n• Excess nitrogen fertilization\r\n• Dense planting patterns\r\n• Root or leaf injuries\r\n• Poor water management', 1, '• Regular weeding and field sanitation\r\n• Remove and destroy infected plant debris\r\n• Avoid mechanical injury to plants during field operations\r\n• Practice crop rotation where possible\r\n• Synchronize planting with neighbors to reduce inoculum', 1, '• Wilting of seedlings\r\n• Small water-soaked stripes along upper leaf margins\r\n• Lesions may appear but are limited', '2026-03-17 09:54:43.665344', '', '', '', 70),
(15, 'Apply copper-based bactericide immediately. Improve field drainage and reduce nitrogen. Remove infected leaves.', 'Moderate BLB infection requires immediate intervention with both cultural and chemical control.', 31, 70, 4, '• Apply copper-based bactericide (e.g., copper hydroxide) at recommended rates\n• Spray at 7-10 day intervals for 2-3 applications\n• Ensure good spray coverage on both leaf surfaces\n• Apply during early morning or late afternoon to avoid phytotoxicity', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.905577', '• Drain excess water from the field\n• Stop nitrogen fertilization temporarily\n• Remove severely infected plants and leaves\n• Improve air circulation by removing weeds\n• Monitor field daily for spread patterns', '• Susceptible rice variety\n• High humidity and frequent rains\n• Excess nitrogen fertilization\n• Dense planting patterns\n• Root or leaf injuries\n• Poor water management', 1, '• Plan to use resistant varieties in next season\n• Keep detailed records of infection patterns\n• Coordinate with neighboring farmers for area-wide management\n• Consult with local DA technician for variety recommendations', 2, '• Extensive water-soaked stripes along leaf margins\n• Lesions coalescing and blighting leaves\n• Yellowing and drying of affected areas\n• Potential impact on panicle exertion', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.905630', '', '', '', 70),
(16, 'URGENT: Consult DA technician immediately. Apply bactericide program. Consider field abandonment if >80% affected.', 'Severe BLB outbreak requires professional guidance and may result in significant yield loss.', 71, 100, 4, '• Follow DA technician recommendations for bactericide program\r\n• Multiple applications of copper-based bactericides required\r\n• Antibiotics may be recommended in severe cases (by DA only)\r\n• Combine with field sanitation for best results', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.920581', '• Contact DA field technician immediately\r\n• Document infection levels with photos\r\n• Drain field completely if possible\r\n• Remove and burn severely infected plants\r\n• Do not use affected field for seed source', '• Highly susceptible variety in widespread use\r\n• Prolonged heavy rainfall\r\n• Excessive nitrogen application\r\n• Previous season infection not managed\r\n• Dense planting with poor drainage', 1, '• MANDATORY: Plant resistant varieties in next season\r\n• Deep plow immediately after harvest\r\n• Allow field to dry completely and expose to sunlight for 2-3 weeks\r\n• Consider soil solarization during summer fallow\r\n• Coordinate with local farmers for synchronized resistant variety adoption\r\n• Report outbreak to Municipal Agriculture Office for area-wide response', 10, '• Widespread leaf blighting across the field\r\n• Wilting and death of entire tillers\r\n• Severe impact on panicle emergence\r\n• White to gray bacterial ooze visible in early morning\r\n• Rapid disease progression', '2026-02-17 07:18:31.210718', '', '', '', 70),
(17, 'Plant resistant varieties. Monitor field daily. Apply balanced fertilizer and maintain shallow water level.', 'Early detection and resistant varieties are key to preventing blast epidemics.', 0, 30, 7, '• Systemic fungicide (e.g., tricyclazole, tebuconazole) at first sign of symptoms\n• Apply preventively in blast-prone areas during tillering\n• Rotate fungicide active ingredients to prevent resistance', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.964884', '• Use certified resistant varieties (check DA recommendations annually)\n• Raise seedlings in wetbed nursery to reduce early infection\n• Avoid dense planting - follow recommended spacing\n• Apply balanced fertilization - avoid late nitrogen\n• Maintain 2-5 cm shallow water depth\n• Split nitrogen application to avoid excess vegetative growth', '• Susceptible variety\n• High humidity (>90%)\n• Long dew periods (8+ hours)\n• Excessive nitrogen and phosphorus\n• Dense planting\n• Cool temperatures (20-25°C)', 1, '• Incorporate rice straw (silica source) after harvest\n• Apply silica amendments if available\n• Scout fields 2-3 times per week during critical growth stages\n• Remove volunteer rice plants (can harbor fungus)\n• Coordinate variety selection with neighboring farmers', 1, '• Small diamond or spindle-shaped spots with brown borders\n• Gray or white centers on lesions\n• Spots appear on leaf blades, typically starting from tips', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.964920', '', '', '', 70),
(18, 'Apply systemic fungicide immediately. Stop nitrogen application. Remove severely infected leaves. Consult DA for variety change.', 'Moderate blast infection can rapidly escalate and requires aggressive management.', 31, 70, 7, '• Immediate application of systemic fungicide (tricyclazole, azoxystrobin)\n• Repeat application at 7-10 day intervals for 2-3 sprays\n• Use combination or alternating products to prevent resistance\n• Ensure thorough spray coverage\n• Apply during morning hours for better efficacy', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.974299', '• Stop nitrogen fertilization immediately\n• Drain field partially to reduce humidity\n• Remove severely infected leaves if practical\n• Do not irrigate in late afternoon (reduces dew period)\n• Monitor field twice daily for rapid spread', '• Favorable weather conditions persisting\n• Susceptible variety widely planted\n• Excess nitrogen in soil\n• Inadequate early management', 1, '• Plan variety change for next season - mandatory use resistant variety\n• Document infection patterns and timing\n• Coordinate with local DA for area-wide fungicide program\n• Report severe outbreaks to Municipal Agriculture Office', 2, '• Numerous spindle-shaped lesions with brown borders and gray centers\n• Lesions coalescing and killing leaves\n• Yellowing and dying of infected leaves\n• Disease spreading from lower to upper leaves', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.974354', '', '', '', 70),
(19, 'CRITICAL: Emergency fungicide program required. Consult DA immediately. Expect major yield loss. Plant resistant variety next season.', 'Severe blast epidemic requires emergency response and will cause significant yield reduction.', 71, 100, 7, '• Emergency fungicide program (consult DA for protocol)\n• Combination fungicide products required\n• Apply at 5-7 day intervals through heading stage\n• Include sticker/spreader for better coverage\n• Coordinate spraying with neighbors if epidemic is area-wide', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.982828', '• Contact DA field technician for emergency consultation\n• Document field conditions with photos and GPS location\n• Partial drainage to reduce humidity if possible\n• Cancel late nitrogen applications\n• Prepare for reduced yield', '• Epidemic conditions (high humidity, long dew, cool nights)\n• Highly susceptible variety\n• Favorable weather persisting for weeks\n• Poor early management', 1, '• MANDATORY: Plant blast-resistant variety next season (no exceptions)\n• Deep plow and expose soil after harvest\n• Burn all infected residues (do not incorporate)\n• Participate in area-wide variety replacement program\n• Request DA support for resistant variety seed distribution\n• This field should be flagged for high blast pressure in future seasons', 3, '• Widespread leaf death across field\n• Entire leaves turning brown and dying\n• Infection moving to leaf sheaths and culms\n• High risk of neck blast at heading stage\n• Possible field failure', '2026-02-17 03:49:02.982864', '', '', '', 70),
(20, 'Use resistant varieties. Avoid excess nitrogen at late stages. Apply preventive fungicide at heading if blast is present.', 'Neck blast prevention is critical as it directly impacts grain formation and yield.', 0, 30, 10, '• Preventive fungicide application at 5-10% heading stage if leaf blast occurred\n• Systemic fungicide (tricyclazole, tebuconazole, azoxystrobin)\n• Second application at 50-70% heading if needed\n• Critical timing: must apply before panicles fully emerged\n• Use high water volume for good coverage inside canopy', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.033043', '• Plant resistant varieties (critical for neck blast prevention)\n• Avoid nitrogen application after panicle initiation\n• Use split nitrogen application - avoid late season excess\n• Maintain proper water management during heading\n• Ensure adequate Potassium and Silica nutrition\n• Wider spacing to improve air circulation at heading', '• Same as leaf blast: susceptible variety, high humidity, dew, cool weather\n• Excess nitrogen during reproductive stage\n• Presence of leaf blast earlier in season\n• Dense canopy at heading', 1, '• Monitor fields closely from panicle initiation through heading\n• If leaf blast was present, preventive neck blast spray is recommended\n• Incorporate rice straw for silica amendment\n• Coordinate spray timing with neighbors for area-wide suppression\n• Document infection levels for future variety decisions', 1, '• Dark brown to black lesion on panicle neck (node below panicle)\n• Infected panicles may remain upright (do not fill)\n• Panicle may break at infection point\n• Discolored or unfilled grains', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.033096', '', '', '', 70),
(21, 'URGENT: Apply fungicide if heading is still ongoing. Accept yield loss. MANDATORY: Use resistant variety next season.', 'Once neck blast symptoms appear, yield loss is inevitable. Focus on preventing further spread.', 31, 100, 10, '• Fungicide application only worthwhile if heading is ongoing\n• Emergency protocol: consult DA technician\n• Multiple fungicide applications at 5-day intervals\n• Will not recover infected panicles but may protect remaining ones', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.043014', '• If any panicles still emerging, contact DA for emergency advice\n• Document yield loss for potential disaster assistance\n• Harvest early to prevent secondary grain infection\n• Do not use this field for seed production\n• Plan for resistant variety in next season', '• Epidemic blast conditions during heading\n• No preventive fungicide applied\n• Highly susceptible variety\n• Excess nitrogen during reproductive growth', 1, '• This field experienced severe blast pressure - mark for future reference\n• MANDATORY: Use resistant variety next season\n• Participate in area-wide blast management program\n• Burn all infected residues after harvest\n• Early plowing and field exposure to sunlight\n• Consider earlier planting next season to avoid peak blast weather', 2, '• Widespread neck rot across field\n• Many panicles broken or unfilled\n• Significant number of white/empty panicles\n• Infection visible on multiple tillers per hill', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.043054', '', '', '', 70),
(22, 'Use proper spacing. Avoid excess nitrogen. Maintain field sanitation. Monitor water line for early lesions.', 'Early sheath blight is managed through cultural practices to limit spread.', 0, 30, 6, '• Fungicide generally not needed at this stage\r\n• Monitor closely for spread before deciding on fungicide\r\n• If spreading: validamycin, propiconazole, or azoxystrobin', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.075139', '• Use proper plant spacing (20x20 cm or wider)\r\n• Avoid excess nitrogen - follow soil test recommendations\r\n• Maintain shallow water depth (2-5 cm)\r\n• Remove weeds that increase humidity\r\n• Improve air circulation in canopy', '• Susceptible variety\r\n• High humidity and frequent rainfall\r\n• Excess nitrogen fertilization\r\n• Dense planting\r\n• Deep water levels', 1, '• Scout at water line weekly during tillering\r\n• Remove infected plants if only a few hills affected\r\n• Drain field temporarily if possible\r\n• Document infection pattern for future management', 5, '• Greenish-gray oval or irregular spots on leaf sheath near water line\r\n• Lesions may have brown border\r\n• Initial spots 1-3 cm in size', '2026-03-08 03:53:59.950311', '', '', '', 70),
(23, 'Apply fungicide (validamycin or propiconazole) immediately. Improve air circulation. Bury infected plant residue after harvest.', 'Moderate to severe sheath blight requires fungicide intervention and improved cultural practices.', 31, 100, 6, '• Immediate fungicide application required\r\n• Validamycin (recommended): apply at early infection, repeat at 10-14 days\r\n• Propiconazole or azoxystrobin as alternatives\r\n• Apply fungicide to lower canopy, target sheaths near water line\r\n• Use adequate water volume for good coverage\r\n• Apply during morning hours', '2026-02-17 03:49:03.085092', '• Stop nitrogen application\r\n• Drain field partially to reduce humidity (alternate wetting/drying)\r\n• Remove weeds to improve airflow\r\n• Avoid late afternoon irrigation\r\n• Monitor twice weekly for disease progress', '• Favorable conditions persisting\r\n• Dense canopy with poor air circulation\r\n• High nitrogen in soil\r\n• Continuous flooding', 1, '• Collect and bury infected plant residues after harvest\r\n• Do not burn (sclerotia survive burning)\r\n• Deep plowing to bury inoculum\r\n• Crop rotation with non-rice crop if possible\r\n• Plan for wider spacing next season\r\n• Consider more resistant variety for next planting', 2, '• Coalescing lesions spreading up the sheath\r\n• Lesions reaching leaf blades\r\n• White fungal mycelia visible in humid conditions\r\n• Potential panicle infection\r\n• Yellowing and death of infected tissue', '2026-03-08 07:38:09.922978', '', '', '', 70),
(24, 'a', '', 91, 100, 2, 'ewrwe', '2026-03-05 12:59:17.967834', 'ewrwerew', '• ok\r\n• nice', 1, 'ewrew', 5, '', '2026-03-05 13:15:23.802855', '', '', '', 70),
(25, 'URGENT: Consult DA technician immediately. Apply bactericide program. Consider field abandonment if >80% affected.', '', 0, 100, 5, '', '2026-03-05 13:17:48.079265', '', '• Noneaa', 1, '', 10, '', '2026-03-05 14:16:10.754265', '', '', '', 70),
(26, 'unhealthy', '', 0, 100, 19, '', '2026-03-08 02:26:21.393157', '', '• atangya', 1, '', 5, '', '2026-03-08 02:26:21.393183', 'spray', 'malusog play', '', 70),
(27, 'unhealthy', '', 0, 100, 19, '', '2026-03-08 02:27:55.007208', '', '• tuyo', 1, '', 1, '', '2026-03-08 02:30:45.386018', 'patubig', 'healthy', '', 70);
